    59	name: changeset-review
    60	version: 1.0.0
    61	
    62	states:
    63	  split:
    64	    description: Coordinator writes an architectural overview of the change, then spawns one review task per logical part plus an aggregator task.
    65	    initial: true
    66	    instructions: |
    67	      You are the change-review coordinator for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.
    68	
    69	      First, treat this instantiated workspace as a scratchpad. Resolve the
    70	      repository root with `git rev-parse --show-toplevel` from the current
    71	      workspace and use that repository root for all VCS commands and all
    72	      repository file lookups (`docs/specs`, source files, ADRs, etc.). Do
    73	      not assume the workspace directory itself contains the repository
    74	      files.
    75	
    76	      0. Resolve `PR#42` to a concrete set of files and a diff.
    77	         The reference can be any of:
    78	           - a PR URL or PR number (e.g., `#42`, `org/repo#42`, full URL)
    79	           - a branch name (compare against the project's default branch)
    80	           - a commit SHA or range `base..head`
    81	           - a path to a `.diff` or `.patch` file on disk
    82	         Use the project's VCS tooling (`gh`, `git diff`, `git log`, etc.)
    83	         from the resolved repository root to produce the list of changed
    84	         files and the unified diff. If the reference is ambiguous, resolve
    85	         it the narrowest way consistent with the user's intent and note the
    86	         assumption in the overview.
    87	      1. Produce an architectural overview of the resolved change.
    88	         Write it to `{output.architecture-overview.path}` covering:
    89	           - the user-visible or operational intent of the change
    90	           - the subsystems touched and how responsibility moves between
    91	             them (component diagram in text is fine)
    92	           - new or changed public interfaces, data models, and contracts
    93	           - cross-cutting concerns introduced (caching, locking,
    94	             migrations, feature flags, deployment ordering)
    95	           - risks the reviewers should keep in mind while reading parts
    96	
    97	         Include a "Metadata" subsection that captures, verbatim or
    98	         summarized:
    99	           - the resolved repository root path
   100	           - whether the change is accompanied by a PR (capture title and
   101	             body if so; leave a `PR: none` note otherwise)
   102	           - the list of commit subjects + bodies on the change
   103	           - whether the project has specs (look for `docs/specs/`,
   104	             `specs/`, `SPEC.md`, ADR directories, or equivalents) that
   105	             intersect the subsystems touched — record the intersecting
   106	             spec file paths or `Specs: none`
   107	
   108	         Include a "User-facing?" call: does the change alter behavior
   109	         visible to users or operators (public API, CLI, UI, error
   110	         messages, defaults, configuration surface, docs-worthy
   111	         behavior)? Record `yes` or `no` with a one-line justification.
   112	
   113	         This is the reviewer's mental map — keep it short and concrete.
   114	
   115	      2. Using the overview, decide which parts need to be reviewed.
   116	         The part set is a mix of **code parts** and **meta parts**.
   117	
   118	         Code parts:
   119	           - Split the diff into logical parts (by subsystem, by file
   120	             cluster, or by concern). Aim for parts small enough to
   121	             review thoroughly in one pass.
   122	
   123	         Meta parts — add each only when the condition holds:
   124	           - `pr-description` — add **if** the change arrived as a PR.
   125	             The task reviews the PR title and body for clarity,
   126	             completeness, release-note readiness, missing context, and
   127	             any security disclosure or breaking-change notes that
   128	             should be called out.
   129	           - `commit-messages` — add **always**. The task reviews the
   130	             list of commit messages for clarity, atomicity, traceability
   131	             (issue / ticket references), and "mess" — `wip`, `fixup`,
   132	             `address review comments`, typo-level fixups, or
   133	             conflicting intent that should be squashed or rewritten
   134	             before merge.
   135	           - `documentation` — add **if** "User-facing?" is `yes`.
   136	             Scope is README, CHANGELOG, `docs/`, API reference, CLI
   137	             help, and any other user-facing docs that must keep up
   138	             with the change. The task body lists the specific doc
   139	             files the coordinator believes need updating or verifying.
   140	           - `spec` — add **if** the project has specs that intersect
   141	             the subsystems touched. Scope is those specific spec files.
   142	             The task reviews whether the change is consistent with the
   143	             spec, whether the spec needs an update, and whether
   144	             assumptions baked into the change match documented behavior.
   145	
   146	      3. Write a short manifest of parts to `{output.parts-manifest.path}`.
   147	         Each entry records:
   148	           - a stable slug (lowercase, hyphenated)
   149	           - `type: code | pr-description | commit-messages | documentation | spec`
   150	           - the files, paths, or materials in scope (for meta parts,
   151	             inline the PR body or commit messages directly so the
   152	             reviewer does not have to re-fetch them)
   153	           - a one-line summary of what to focus on
   154	           - a pointer back to the relevant section of the overview
   155	
   156	      4. For every part, append a task file under `tasks/` named
   157	         `NN-review-<slug>.md` with:
   158	           - `### Task review-<slug>: Review <part title>`
   159	           - `**State:** review`
   160	           - `**Prior:** Task {task_id}`
